Part 1: Spatial Weights, Spatial Autocorrelation, Polygons¶

This example follows the SciPy 18 Chapter 6 - Exploratory Spatial Data Analysis (ESDA) using Pysal. However, some additional material on contiguity weights is included. The data file is the same Buffalo Open Data file used in the Spatial Processing exercise.

Join counts (from scipy 18 lab)¶

One way to formalize a test for spatial autocorrelation in a binary attribute is to consider the so-called joins. A join exists for each neighbor pair of observations, and the joins are reflected in our binary spatial weights object qW.

Each unit can take on one of two values "Black" or "White", and so for a given pair of neighboring locations there are three different types of joins that can arise:

  • Black Black (BB)
  • White White (WW)
  • Black White (or White Black) (BW)

Given that we have 143 Black polygons on our map, what is the number of Black Black (BB) joins we could expect if the process were such that the Black polygons were randomly assigned on the map? This is the logic of join count statistics.

We can use the esda package from PySAL to carry out join count analysis:

In [37]:
import esda 
yb = 1 * (y > y.median()) # convert back to binary
#wq =  lp.weights.Queen.from_dataframe(df)
qW.transform = 'b'
np.random.seed(12345)
jc = esda.join_counts.Join_Counts(yb, qW)
In [38]:
jc.bb #number of black/black neighbors
Out[38]:
331
In [39]:
jc.ww #number of white/white neighbors
Out[39]:
317
In [40]:
jc.bw #number of black/white neighbors
Out[40]:
204

from Scipy2018 06 ESDA:

The critical question is whether the number of BB neighbors is a departure from what we would expect if the process generating the spatial distribution of the Black polygons were a completely random one?

To answer this, PySAL uses random spatial permutations of the observed attribute values to generate a realization under the null hypothesis of Complete Spatial Randomness (CSR). This is repeated a large number of times (999 default) to construct a reference distribution to evaluate the statistical significance of our observed counts.

The average number of BB joins from the synthetic realizations is:

In [41]:
jc.mean_bb
Out[41]:
210

which is less than the observed count = 331. The question is whether the observed value is so different from the expectation that we would reject the null of CSR?

In [42]:
import seaborn as sbn
sbn.kdeplot(jc.sim_bb, shade=True)
plt.vlines(jc.bb, 0, 1, color='r')#red line at observed value
plt.vlines(jc.mean_bb, 0,1)# black line at mean value
plt.xlabel('BB Counts');
In [43]:
jc.p_sim_bb #pseudo p-value
Out[43]:
0.001

Since this is below conventional significance levels, we would reject the null of complete spatial randomness in favor of spatial autocorrelation in hispanic population residence.
